04137nam a22006375i 9780674269743DE-B159720220110023848.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220110t20212021mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742697437 a10.4159/97806742697432doi  a(DE-B1597)590538  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aHX517.8aHM1131 7aHIS0370702bisacsh04a335.009172/42231 aFriedman, Jeremy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRipe for Revolution :bBuilding Socialism in the Third World /cJeremy Friedman. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (352 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA historical account of ideology in the Global South as the postwar laboratory of socialism, its legacy following the Cold War, and the continuing influence of socialist ideas worldwide. In the first decades after World War II, many newly independent Asian and African countries and established Latin American states pursued a socialist development model. Jeremy Friedman traces the socialist experiment over forty years through the experience of five countries: Indonesia, Chile, Tanzania, Angola, and Iran. These states sought paths to socialism without formal adherence to the Soviet bloc or the programs that Soviets, East Germans, Cubans, Chinese, and other outsiders tried to promote. Instead, they attempted to forge new models of socialist development through their own trial and error, together with the help of existing socialist countries, demonstrating the flexibility and adaptability of socialism. All five countries would become Cold War battlegrounds and regional models, as new policies in one shaped evolving conceptions of development in another. Lessons from the collapse of democracy in Indonesia were later applied in Chile, just as the challenge of political Islam in Indonesia informed the policies of the left in Iran. Efforts to build agrarian economies in West Africa influenced Tanzania’s approach to socialism, which in turn influenced the trajectory of the Angolan model. Ripe for Revolution shows socialism as more adaptable and pragmatic than often supposed. When we view it through the prism of a Stalinist orthodoxy, we miss its real effects and legacies, both good and bad. To understand how socialism succeeds and fails, and to grasp its evolution and potential horizons, we must do more than read manifestos. We must attend to history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 10. Jan 2022) 0aGlobalizationzDeveloping countries. 0aGlobalizationzSouthern Hemisphere. 0aSocialismzDeveloping countries. 0aSocialismzSouthern Hemisphere. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 20th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073911440uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/978067426974340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674269743423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674269743/original  a978-3-11-073911-4  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK